As set out in the [http://www.che.ac.za/documents/d000004/Higher_Education_Act.pdf Higher Education Act No 101 of 1997], the university is governed by the Council with the [[Cheryl de la Rey|Vice-Chancellor & Principal]] the executive head responsible for the day-to-day administration and the Chancellor being the non-resident titular head of the university.<ref>[http://web.up.ac.za/default.asp?ipkCategoryID=6 Management & Governance Retrieved 8 August 2010]</ref> The Registrar is responsible for the academic administration of the University, as well as legal matters, and is secretary to the University Council and Senate.

The university's academic activities are divided into nine faculties and one business school. Whilst the faculties comprise of 140 departments and 85 institutes, bureaus and centres.<ref>[http://web.up.ac.za/default.asp?ipkCategoryID=1 About UP Retrieved 16 June 2010]</ref>

==Campus==
[[Image:University of Pretoria Old Arts Building.jpg|thumb|left| <center>The Old Arts building now houses several museums </center> ]]

; Main Hatfield Campus
The university<U+2019>s main campus and central administration offices are situated in the suburb of [[Hatfield, Pretoria|Hatfield]], [[Pretoria]] and houses six of the nine faculties.<ref>[http://www.sarua.org/?q=uni_University%20of%20Pretoria University of Pretoria. Retrieved 19 January 2010.]</ref><ref>[http://www.educations.com/University_of_Pretoria__b11259.html University of Pretoria. Retrieved 19 January 2010.]</ref> The campus, bordered by the suburb of [[Brooklyn, Pretoria|Brooklyn]] to the south and Hatfield to the north, was built over 24&nbsp;hectares and has more than 60 buildings of historical value.<ref>[http://web.up.ac.za/sitefiles/StudyInfo2010Jan20.pdf Study Info 2010 Retrieved 11 June 2010]</ref>

Adjacent to the Hatfield campus is the LC de Villiers Sport Grounds & High Performance Centre which were developed on an area of 76 [[Hectare|ha]]. Adjacent to the sport grounds is the university's experimental farm, which is used to conduct field experiments for the Faculty of Natural and Agricultural Sciences.<ref>[http://web.up.ac.za/default.asp?ipkCategoryID=2507 Department of Plant Production and Soil Science Facilities. Retrieved 1 October 2009.]</ref> The campus served is by the Hatfield [[Gautrain]] station connecting Pretoria and Johannesburg. A university bus shuttle services operates between the Hatfield campus and the Groenkloof and Prinshof campuses, whilst a park and ride shuttle service operates between the Hatfield campus and the LC de Villiers Sport Grounds.

===Museums===
The university<U+2019>s art collection consists primarily of paintings, sculptures and graphic works by South African artists including the likes of [[Jacobus Hendrik Pierneef]], Gregoire Boonzaier, [[William Kentridge]] and Sam Ngethwa. The collection also incorporates artworks by renowned international artists among others such as [[Max Pechstein]], [[K<U+00E4>the Kollwitz]], [[Max Lieberman]], [[George Grosz]], [[Otto Mueller]], [[Rembrandt van Rijn]], [[Thomas Hart Benton (painter)|Thomas Benton]] and [[Marc Chagall]]. The university's sculpture collection, the largest such collection in South Africa, contains sculptures by  [[Sidney Kumalo]], [[Maureen Quinn]], [[Michael Teffo]], [[Anton Smit]] and others.<ref>[http://web.up.ac.za/default.asp?ipkCategoryID=10466&sub=1&parentid=5885&subid=10318&ipklookid=14 University of Pretoria Art Collection. Retrieved 1 October 2009.]</ref>

The Old Arts Building was proclaimed a National Monument in 1968<ref>https://www.up.ac.za/dspace/handle/2263/6561 Old Arts Building Retrieved 29 March 2010</ref> and houses the Van Tilburg Collection, Van Gybland-Oosterhoff Collection and Mapungubwe Museum. The '''[[Van Tilburg Collection]]''' is a permanent museum that comprises 17th & 18th century [[furniture]],<ref>[http://web.up.ac.za/default.asp?ipkCategoryID=10849&sub=1&parentid=5885&subid=10318&ipklookid=14 The collection of European furniture. Retrieved 14 September 2009.]</ref> [[paintings]],<ref>[http://web.up.ac.za/default.asp?ipkCategoryID=10850&sub=1&parentid=5885&subid=10318&ipklookid=14 The collection of paintings and graphic works. Retrieved 14 September 2009.]</ref> [[Delft]] [[Ceramics (art)|ceramics]]<ref name="ReferenceA">http://web.up.ac.za/default.asp?ipkCategoryID=10848&sub=1&parentid=5885&subid=10318&ipklookid=14 The ceramic collection. Retrieved 14 September 2009.</ref> and other works of [[art]], and includes the largest South African collection of Chinese [[ceramic]] objects, from the [[Chin Dynasty|Chin]] (221-206&nbsp;B.C.), [[Han Dynasty|Han]] (202&nbsp;B.C. <U+2013> A.D. 220), [[Tang Dynasty|Tang]] (A.D. 618-906), [[Song Dynasty|Song]] (A.D. 960-1279), [[Ming Dynasty|Ming]] (1368<U+2013>1644) and [[Qing Dynasty|Qing]] (1644<U+2013>1912) dynasties.<ref name="ReferenceA"/>{{Rquote|right| What survives are the almost untouched remains of the palace sites and also the entire settlement area dependent upon them, as well as two earlier capital sites, the whole presenting an unrivalled picture of the development of social and political structures over some 400 years.| Unesco,<br />''on the Mapungubwe World Heritage Site''<ref>[http://www.southafrica.info/about/history/mapungubwe.htm Mapungubwe: SA's lost city of gold Retrieved April 24, 2010]</ref>}}The university is the custodian of the collection of artifacts found at the [[Mapungubwe]] National Park and [[World Heritage site]]<ref>[http://www.sanparks.org/parks/mapungubwe/ Mapungubwe National Park and World Heritage Site Retrieved 29 March 2010]</ref><ref>[http://whc.unesco.org/en/list/1099 Mapungubwe Cultural Landscapeand World Heritage Site Retrieved 29 March 2010]</ref> and such display these artifacts in the '''[[Mapungubwe Museum]]'''.<ref>[http://www.southafrica.info/about/history/worldheritagesites.htm World heritage in South Africa]</ref><ref>[http://web.up.ac.za/default.asp?ipkCategoryID=10319&sub=1&parentid=5885&subid=10318&ipklookid=14 Mapungubwe Museum]</ref> Gold ornaments, ivory, bone, ceramic-ware, clay figurines, trade beads, iron and copper artifacts are on permanent public display.<ref>[http://web.up.ac.za/default.asp?ipkCategoryID=10664&sub=1&parentid=5885&subid=10318&ipklookid=14 The Mapungubwe Collection]</ref> The '''[[Van Gybland-Oosterhoff Collection]]''' is a ceramic collection, donated by Dr Horace Hugo Alexander van Gybland Oosterhoff and accepted by the university on 14 March 1939, is the largest collection of objects, publications, memorabilia and photographs of historical interest, relating to Dutch culture outside of the Netherlands.<ref>[http://www.tshwanetourism.co.za/activities/att_upac.php University of Pretoria Art Collections. Retrieved 15 September 2009.]</ref><ref>[http://www.gotravel24.com/travelguides/pretoria/culture-scene Wiki Travel Guides - Culture scene. Retrieved 15 September 2009.]</ref>

The Old Merensky Library houses  the '''[[Edoardo Villa Museum]]'''. The Edoardo Villa Museum currently houses the largest collection of sculptures by the Italian artist [[Edoardo Villa]] and one South Africa's most renowned sculptors, who was mentored by [[Minotti]] at the Scuola D<U+2019>Arte Andrea Fontoniby.<ref>[http://tissuebank.co.za/default.asp?ipkCategoryID=10323&sub=1&parentid=5885&subid=10318&ipklookid=14 Edoardo Villa Museum. Retrieved 1 October 2009.]</ref><ref>[http://www.artnet.com/Artists/ArtistHomePage.aspx?artist_id=24805&page_tab=Bio_and_links Edoardo Villa. Retrieved 1 October 2009.]</ref>

The '''[[Van Wouw Museum]]''' is the largest collection of bronze, marble and plaster sculptures by the famous pioneer South African sculptor, Anton van Wouw (1862<U+2013>1945).<ref>[http://web.up.ac.za/sitefiles/file/web-team/UP%20in%20a%20Nutshell%202009.pdf Up in a Nutshell 17 September 2009]</ref> Van Wouw, who is widely regarded as the founder of traditional sculpture in South Africa,<ref>[http://www.sahistory.org.za/pages/people/bios/vanwouw-a.htm Anton van Wouw. Retrieved 17 September 2009.]</ref> created masterful artworks portraying Boer figures and the indigenous peoples of South Africa. Besides documents, photos, paintings and tools the exhibits are mainly [[bronze]] [[maquette]]s and casts of Van Wouw's sculptural work.<ref>[http://web.up.ac.za/default.asp?ipkCategoryID=10877&sub=1&parentid=5885&subid=10318&ipklookid=14 African Studies by Anton Van Wouw]</ref> The Van Wouw Museum is housed in [[Anton Van Wouw]]'s last residence,<ref>[http://web.up.ac.za/default.asp?ipkCategoryID=10878&sub=1&parentid=5885&subid=10318&ipklookid=14 History of the Van Wouw House]</ref> a Dutch national monument.

Other minor art collections include the [[Christo Coetzee]] collection which was bequeathed to the university by the artist in 2001 and consists of more than 3000 objects,  NPK Ceramics Collection, [[Hilgard Muller]] Collection, Mike Edwards Collection, [[Paul Kruger|Kruger]] Collection, [[Frans Esterhuizen]] Cartoon Collection, [[Hansie Visagie]] Puppet Collection, Friends of the Pretoria Art Association Art Collection, [[Baldinelli]] Trust Collection and [[Mimi Coertse]] Collection.

The University's Science, Engineering and Technology (SET) Discovery Centre, '''Sci-Enza''', was officially launched in 1977.<ref name="UPCOZA-AboutUs">{{cite web|url=http://web.up.ac.za/default.asp?ipkCategoryID=2064&subid=2064&ipklookid=11|title=About us|publisher=University of Pretoria|accessdate=2009-11-02}}</ref> The Discovery Centre is an umbrella complex where young children, students and adults can explore the world of science, engineering and technology in a "play-as-you-learn" way.<ref name="UPCOZA-AboutUs"/> Activities at the Centre museum include: a Digital [[planetarium]]; Exploratorium; [[Camera Obscura]];<ref>[http://web.up.ac.za/default.asp?ipkCategoryID=2096&subid=2096&ipklookid=11 Camera Obscura. Retrieved 1 October 2009.]</ref> Biological science exhibit; Botanical garden;<ref>[http://web.up.ac.za/default.asp?ipkCategoryID=3525 Manie van der Schijff Botanical Garden. Retrieved 1 October 2009.]</ref> Indigenous technology exhibit<ref>[http://web.up.ac.za/default.asp?ipkCategoryID=10319 Mapungubwe Museum. Retrieved 1 October 2009.]</ref>

