===Key places===
{{Main|Kya Rosa|Merensky Library}}

[[File:Hendrik pretorius university pretoria chapel.jpg|thumb|right| <center>The University Chapel </center>]]
[[File:Die skip University of pretoria.JPG|right|thumb| <center>The Administration Building, or the Ship as it<U+2019>s colloquially known, at the corner of Lynnwood and University Roads.<ref>https://www.up.ac.za/dspace/handle/2263/6558 Administration Building. Retrieved 18 September 2009.</ref> </center>]] 

The main hall and site of ceremonies, the Aula, was designed by Karel Jooste and completed in 1958. The Aula was the first Opera House to be built in the capital and remained the major venue in the city until the State Theatre's completion in the early 1980s.<ref>[http://www.up.ac.za/dspace/handle/2263/6795 Aula & Rautenbach Hall Retrieved April 24, 2010]</ref> The 1012 seater auditorium<ref>[http://web.up.ac.za/sitefiles/file/5885/Aula%20Theatre%20Specifications.pdf Aula Theatre Specifications Retrieved April 24, 2010]</ref> has played host to foreign dignitaries, presidents,<ref>[http://www.info.gov.za/speeches/2007/07012516151004.htm Media programme for state visit to South Africa by Chinese President Hu Jintao Retrieved April 24, 2010]</ref> local and international artists.<ref>[http://web.up.ac.za/default.asp?ipkCategoryID=10472&subid=10472 Lunch hour concerts Retrieved April 24, 2010]</ref> The main music complex, comprising the 500 seater Musaion and 3000 seater Amphitheatre was built between 1960-1964<ref name="autogenerated1"/> The University Chapel, formally the Church of [[Saint Alfons Maria de Liguori]], and the accompanying Monastery was built in 1925 and was bought from the Catholic Church in 1980. Saint Alfons, who was canonised in 1839, was the founder of the order of Ligournians (or [[Redemptorists]]), an order founded in 1732 in Naples, Italy and dedicated to helping underprivileged communities.<ref>https://www.up.ac.za/dspace/handle/2263/6560 Chapel (Old Monastery). Retrieved 18 September 2009.</ref>

===Other campuses===
;Onderstepoort

The possibility of training veterinarians in South Africa was frequently raised after the first Colonial Veterinary Surgeon in South Africa was appointed in approximately 1874, but it was not until 1920 that the Swiss-born veterinarian, Sir [[Arnold Theiler]], was appointed as Director of Veterinary Education and Research at Onderstepoort under the supervision of the then Transvaal University College. New facilities were inaugurated at the end of 1921 and the first residence was opened in 1924. The first eight South African trained veterinarians qualified in 1924.

The Faculty of Veterinary Sciences was developed on the 65&nbsp;hectares [[Onderstepoort]] campus, with buildings covering a total of 55 000 square meters 30&nbsp;km  north west of the Hatfield main campus and 15&nbsp;km north of the Pretoria city center. The [[Onderstepoort Veterinary Academic Hospital]] provides clinical services rendered with full student participation as part of the primary teaching mission of the Faculty of Veterinary Science.<ref>[http://web.up.ac.za/default.asp?ipkCategoryID=1136&subid=1136&ipklookid=13 Faculty Facilities Retrieved 12 June 2010]</ref>  It's  the only faculty in South Africa educating veterinarians and veterinary nurses.<ref>[http://web.up.ac.za/default.asp?ipkCategoryID=1127&subid=1127&ipklookid=13 Faculty of Veterinary Science About us. Retrieved 29 September 2009.]</ref><ref>[http://www.thsinfo.co.za/20080612_websiteONDERSTEPOORT.doc The Faculty of Veterinary Science. Retrieved 29 September 2009.]</ref>

;Groenkloof 
During the Conference of Teachers in Town and Refugee Camp Schools of the Transvaal and Orange River Colony of 1-10 July 1902 a resolution was passed to establish <U+201C>Normal Schools<U+201D> for the education of teachers in Johannesburg and Pretoria. The Pretoria Normal School, housed in a house in 126 Rissik Street commences with one student in 1902, growing to 19 by year end. In 1903 the Johannesburg Normal School's 40 students are transferred to Pretoria when it is closed and the Pretoria and Johannesburg institutions are merged to form the Transvaal Normal College. When the Transvaal University College is established in 1908 the first students include students from the Transvaal Normal College. 1909 the school is renamed the Pretoria Normal College when new teacher training facilities are established in Heidelberg and Johannesburg. In 1954 the school is again renamed to the "Onderwyskollege van Pretoria<U+201D> or Teachers College Pretoria. In 1974 the University of Pretoria took over the sole responsibility for training secondary teacher from the Teachers College Pretoria. 

Although the Teachers College Pretoria bought new college grounds in Groenkloof during 1975, the college only occupies the new grounds in 1988 and inaugurated in 1989. The Johannesburg "Goudstadse Onderwyskollege<U+201D>, Transvaal College of Education, Laudium and the Transvaal Education College Soshanguve amalgamate and move their operations to the Teachers College Pretoria in 1993 and the latter two in 1998 respectively. In 2000 the Teachers Training College Pretoria was incorporated into the university<U+2019>s Faculty of Education, which saw the faculty moving from the main Hatfield campus to the self-sufficient [[Groenkloof]] campus.<ref>[http://web.up.ac.za/default.asp?ipkCategoryID=43&subid=43&ipklookid=6&parentid= Welcome to the Faculty of Education. Retrieved 29 September 2009.]</ref><ref>http://www.ais.up.ac.za/edu/docs/HistoryEduLib.pdf A Chronological History Retrieved 29 December 2011</ref>

;Prinshof

Health Sciences are taught at the [[Prinshof]] Campus, adjoining the [[Steve Biko Hospital]] (Formerly Pretoria Academic Hospital) the main healthcare training facility of the university and the [[Tshwane District Hospital]].<ref>[http://web.up.ac.za/default.asp?ipkCategoryID=1268&subid=1268 Faculty of Health Sciences Initiatives. Retrieved 29 September 2009.]</ref> Additional health care training facilities include the [[Kalafong Hospital]] on the western outskirts of Pretoria in the suburb of Attridgeville and the [[Weskoppies Psychiatric Hospital]] west of the city centre and built on the site of the old Pretoria botanical gardens.

;Illovo
The university's business school, the [[Gordon Institute of Business Science]] (GIBS), is situated in a [[Greenfield land|greenfield]] campus in the [[Illovo, Gauteng|Illovo]] Boulevard, mixed-use commercial node between the suburbs of [[Rosebank, Gauteng|Rosebank]] and [[Sandton]] in Johannesburg,<ref>[http://www.illovoboulevard.com/about.php About the Ilovo Boulevard Retrieved March 29, 2009]</ref> with a satellite Inner City Campus on Pritchard Street.<ref>http://www.gibs.co.za/about-us/na_5/inner-city-campus.aspx Inner City Campus Retrieved May 13, 2011</ref> The Illovo campus is served by the [[Rosebank (Gautrain station)|Rosebank Gautrain]] station, with a nearby Gautrain bus stop and the inner city campus by the [[Johannesburg Park Station]]. GIBS Europe operates out of [[London]], United Kingdom offering company specific programmes.

;Other sites
The [[Witbank]] and [[Hammanskraal]] satellite campuses, were established in 1988 and 1994 respectively and are used as additional practical facilities and for community engagement.<ref>[http://web.up.ac.za/default.asp?ipkCategoryID=5056 University of Pretoria Historic Overview. Retrieved 29 September 2009.]</ref> The now defunct [[Vista University]]'s [[Mamelodi]] campus was incorporated on 2 January 2004, as part of the restructuring of South African tertiary institutions.<ref>[http://web.up.ac.za/default.asp?ipkCategoryID=82 Mamelodi campus. Retrieved 29 September 2009.]</ref> The Mamelodi campus hosts the extended BSc degree programme and functions as the community engagement hub for the university.<ref>http://matric.mg.co.za/university-of-pretoria/ University of Pretoria 29 December 2011</ref>

==Academics==
===Library system===
{{seealso|University of Pretoria Library Services|University of Pretoria Special Collections|Merensky Library, University of Pretoria}}

{{Rquote|right| <U+201C>This country has given me so much that I am only too happy to be allowed to help it to develop and to be able to give back to it a fraction of what it has given to me<U+201D>.| Dr. [[Hans Merensky]] <br /> at the opening of the Merensky Library <U+201D>.<ref>https://www.up.ac.za/dspace/handle/2263/6526. Retrieved 10 September 2009.</ref> }}
[[File:University of Pretoria Merensky Library.jpg|thumb|left| <center>The Old [[Merensky Library]] </center>]]
[[File:Old merensky.jpg|thumb|left|200px| <center>The Old [[Merensky Library]], a national monument </center>]]
In 1933 the University decided that the library collection necessitated the building of a new library building, the collection which at that time was kept in the Old Arts building. The library was designed by the South African architect Gerard Moerdijk, following a donation of <U+00A3>10 000 from mining geologist Dr. Hans Merensky and construction started in 1937.<ref name="up.ac.za">https://www.up.ac.za/dspace/handle/2263/6526 Old Merensky Library. Retrieved 18 September 2009.</ref> Drawing from his inspiration from Persia and Africa, the design of the building incorporates several architectural styles including Art Deco, Neo-Classicism, Arts and Crafts, Cape Dutch and Regency. The Old Merensky Library was proclaimed a National Monument in 1991.<ref>[http://www.friedlandart.com/edoardovillamuseum.html Old Merensky Library Retrieved 29 March 2010]</ref> 

Despite expansions to the Old Merensky Library in 1957, the library subsequently became insufficient to meet the growing needs of the institution and in 1975 the Merensky Library II was completed, currently housing 7 of 9 the faculty libraries.<ref>[http://www.library.up.ac.za/aboutus/history.htm Historical Background. Retrieved 2 October 2009.]</ref> Besides the main Merensky Library complex, the university library system also includes the separately administered Jotello F Soga Library (Veterinary Science), Oliver R Tambo Law Library, Education Library, Mamelodi Library and Health Sciences Library.<ref>http://www.library.up.ac.za/aboutus/index.htm About Us Retrieved April 28, 2011</ref>

The Oliver R Tambo Law Library houses the [[University of Pretoria Faculty of Law|Faculty of Law]]'s collection of legal materials and the Law of Africa collection in the library is the single most comprehensive and current collection of primary legal materials of African countries.<ref name="ReferenceA">http://web.up.ac.za/default.asp?ipkCategoryID=15428&subid=15428&ipklookid=10 About the ICLA Retrieved June 27, 2011</ref>

In 1974 the Jotello F Soga Library of the [[University of Pretoria Faculty of Veterinary Science|Faculty of Veterinary Science]] at the Onderstepoort campus was established and is named in honour of Dr [[Jotello Festiri Soga]] the first South African  qualified as a veterinary surgeon.<ref>http://www.library.up.ac.za/vet/about.htm#overview out the Library Retrieved 21 December 2011</ref>

In 2006 the University established [[UPSpace]], its own open access digital research repository.<ref>https://www.up.ac.za/dspace/ UPSpace. Retrieved 2 October 2009.</ref> and the university's library has since become one of 27 partners in the [[World Digital Library]] project.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wdl.org/en/about/partners.html |title=About the World Digital Library: Partners |accessdate=2009-04-21}}</ref> In January 2011 the Webometrics World Ranking of Institutional Repositories ranked UPeTD,  the university's repository of electronic theses and dissertations, 133rd in the world.<ref>[http://repositories.webometrics.info/toprep.asp?offset=100 Top 400 World repositories Retrieved 21 January 2011]</ref>

===Research===
[[File:University of Pretoria Humanities building.jpg|thumb|right| <center>The Faculty of Humanities building, designed by alumnus Brian Sandrock, was constructed over Roper Street in 1977<ref>https://www.up.ac.za/dspace/handle/2263/6916 Human Sciences Building. Retrieved 18 September 2009.</ref> </center>]]
The university's achievements and performance in research locally and internationally, including its collaboration and cooperation with the private sector, industry, science councils, foundations and [[NGO]]<U+2019>s, the large number of graduates that it produces (particularly doctoral and other postgraduate students) as well as scientists and engineers<ref>[http://web.up.ac.za/default.asp?ipkCategoryID=942&subid=942&ipklookid=7 Message from the Dean, Prof Roelf Sandenbergh. Retrieved 17 September 2009.]</ref> and its focus on innovation,<ref>[http://web.up.ac.za/default.asp?ipkCategoryID=2843&ArticleID=22 Ready to face the future and inspire a generation. Retrieved 17 September 2009.]</ref> contribute directly towards enhancing the South Africa's competitiveness.<ref>http://www.mg.co.za/article/2008-02-18-eyeing-the-oxbridge-league http://www.mg.co.za/article/2008-02-18-eyeing-the-oxbridge-league. Retrieved 17 September 2009.</ref> Multidisciplinary research is encouraged through several institutional and faculty wide research themes and research groups clustered around these themes.<ref>http://web.up.ac.za/default.asp?ipkCategoryID=17735&subid=17735&ipklookid=1 UP Institutional & Faculty Research Themes Retrieved 28 December 2011</ref> A 2010 report by Centre for Higher Education Transformation identified the university as a top research-intensive university in South Africa.<ref name="uwn">{{cite news |first=Karen |last=McGregor |title=SOUTH AFRICA: New university clusters emerge |url=http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=20100523104119724 |work=University World News |date=23 May 2010 |accessdate=11 June 2010}}</ref> The university is member of the [[CDIO]] engineering education initiative and international collaboration.;<ref>[http://www.engsc.ac.uk/er/cdio/index.asp CDIO Retrieved March 29, 2010]</ref><ref>[http://www.cdio.org/implementing-cdio-your-institution/collaboration CDIO Retrieved March 29, 2010]</ref>
{{Main|Southern Education and Research Alliance}}

In 1999 a strategic alliance was formed between the University of Pretoria and the [[Council for Scientific and Industrial Research]] (CSIR).<ref>[http://www.seralliance.com/pdfs/sera_annual_review_2002.pdf Highlights and Achievements. Retrieved 10 September 2009.]</ref> This alliance, which is known as the [http://www.seralliance.com/ Southern Education and Research Alliance] (SERA), collaborates locally and internationally with universities, NGO<U+2019>s, companies and multinational bodies in various research areas.<ref>[http://www.seralliance.com/pdfs/sera_relationships.pdf SERA Relationships and Links. Retrieved 1 October 2009.]</ref> The SERA partners share a vision for a world-class, innovative and market responsive business that delivers appropriate information, facilitates knowledge connectivity through knowledge workers, links the best minds to create a global network, and protects [[intellectual property]]. Through their co-operation the alliance partners aim at fostering a non-exclusive academic, scientific and technological environment that will benefit all participants and the country as a whole.<ref>[http://www.seralliance.com/initiatives.php Key Initiatives. Retrieved 1 October 2009.]</ref><ref>[http://www.seralliance.com/profile.php SERA Profile. Retrieved 1 October 2009.]</ref> Sera has a 50% shareholding in the Innovation Hub, a fully accredited technology park situated on 60&nbsp;hectares of the university's experimental farm.<ref>[http://www.theinnovationhub.com/partners.cfm Our partners - an overview Retrieved 28 May 2010]</ref>

Notable Research includes:
*[[Centre for Human Rights]]
*[[Forestry and Agricultural Biotechnology Institute]] (FABI)
*[[African Centre for Genome Technologies]]

