==Student life==

[[File:Kya rosa.jpg|thumb|right|200px| <center>The [[Kya Rosa]], the original building of the Transvaal University College </center>]]
[[File:University of Pretoria Student Council.jpg|thumb|right|200px| <center>The first student council in 1909 </center>]]
[[File:University of Pretoria RAG.jpg|thumb|right|200px| <center> Rag festivities in Church Square in 1910 </center>]]
[[File:University of Pretoria Welcoming day.jpg|thumb|right|200px| <center> Welcoming day for first years in 1929 </center>]]
[[File:Univeristy of Pretoria First Rag Queen.jpg|thumb|200px|<center>The first Rag Queen was crowned in  1929 </center>]]
[[File:University of Pretoria Spring day.jpg|thumb|right|200px|  <center>Spring day festivities in 1939 </center>]]
[[File:University of Pretoria mascot - Oom Gert.jpg|thumb|right|200px| <center> The university's mascot, Oom Gert in 1939 </center>]]

;Residential life

Residence is provided to students in 24 undergraduate and post graduate residences and 3 post graduate only residences spread over the University's campuses.<ref>http://web.up.ac.za/default.asp?ipkCategoryID=113&subid=113&ipklookid=1 The choice is yours - Residences Retrieved  April 15, 2011</ref> The first students of the Transvaal University College, resided in the [[Kya Rosa]], a Victorian house in Skinner Street. In 1915, the first male residence Kollegetehuis was constructed on the Hatfield campus<ref>http://web.up.ac.za/res.asp?ipkCategoryID=5194&sub=0&parentid=20&subid=113&ipklookid=1 The Republic of Kollegetehuis Retrieved April 25, 2011</ref> and the first female residence Asterhof in 1925.<ref>http://web.up.ac.za/res.asp?ipkCategoryID=10151&subid=10151&ipklookid=40 About Asterhof Retrieved April 25, 2011</ref> In 1916 Dutch Reformed Church established the Sonop Christelike Tehuis aiming to provide accommodation to the male students of the University, the private residence enjoys an official recognition agreement with University authorities.<ref>http://web.up.ac.za/res.asp?ipkCategoryID=3894 Sonop Retrieved April 25, 2011</ref> Students not living in a University residence can join one of four Day Houses which gives them the opportunity to partake in organised student life activities.<ref>http://web.up.ac.za/default.asp?ipkCategoryID=7754&subid=7754&ipklookid=15 Day Houses Retrieved April 25, 2011</ref>

;Student organisations

Approximately more than 100 student clubs and organisations operate on the university campus.<ref>[http://web.up.ac.za/default.asp?ipkCategoryID=13670&subid=13670&ipklookid=15 Societies Retrieved January 17, 2011]</ref> These include numerous student government, service providers, and service organizations. The most prominent amongst these are the Student Parliament, Student Representative Council, and Constitutional Tribunal (Student Court). The Student Parliament is the plenary body of student governance and determines the wider mandate for student governance. The Student Representative Council (SRC) is the executive body of student governance and subsequently charters and provides most of the funding for other student groups, and represents students' interests when dealing with the administration. The SRC is the residential student government, specializing in programming, policy, and facilities and services. Societies are registered in the following categories as catering for religious, political, social, cultural, academic and other. The Constitutional Tribunal is the judicial body of student governance  and adjudicates disputes primarily between student organisations and its judge<U+2019>s sit on the panel of student disciplinary hearings.  The various service providers are the university<U+2019>s primary programming organisations, serving as a centre of social, cultural, intellectual and recreational life.

;Student activities
The university has a long tradition of student activities and traditions. It is common belief that if a blossom from a [[Jacaranda]] tree falls on your head you will do well in the end of year exams.<ref>[http://gopretoria.co.za/the-jacaranda-city The Jacaranda City Retrieved April 1, 2010]</ref><ref>[http://www.friendsaccsa.com/jacaranda.html Jacaranda (Jacaranda acutifolia Retrieved April 1, 2010]</ref> Other traditions and customs vary by residence, day house and faculty.

The university started the tradition of [[Rag (student society)]] (Afrikaans: Jool), a student-run charitable fundraising organisations, in South Africa in 1925.<ref>[http://www.encyclopedia.com/doc/1G1-174603121.html Retrieved April 1, 2010]</ref> During Rag students take to the streets in a parade of floats whilst collecting money for charity. The university's '''Springday''' celebrations are a declared university holiday and are held annually on the second Wednesday of September and the festivities are only second to the annual Rag.<ref>[http://www.up.ac.za/calendars/2010calendar.pdf Main Calendar dates Retrieved April 1, 2010]</ref>

Student's song and dance competitions include Ienkmelodienk, Serenade and Serrie and the university<U+2019>s Drama Department hosts the annual week long '''Kr<U+00EA>kvars Arts Festival''' each July in the intimate Bok, Lier and Masker theatres on the Hatfield campus. The festival has transformed from an event started in 2000 and centred around the Drama honours students<U+2019> Directing course to an open festival where other students and the public at large are encouraged to put on productions.<ref>[http://www.litnet.co.za/cgi-bin/giga.cgi?cmd=cause_dir_news_item&news_id=3609&cause_id=1270 Krekvars: 50 Different Shows Stretch Tuk's Drama Students Retrieved 8 Augustus 2010]</ref>

The amphitheatre hosts the annual '''Ienkmelodienk''' song and dance competition between the first years of the various residences and day houses in January.<ref>[http://www.perdeby.co.za/an-ienkmelodienk-to-remember/ An Ienkmelodienk to remember Retrieved 8 August 2010]</ref> The annual '''Serenade''' and '''Serrie''' singing competitions between the residences and day houses are held in the Musaion and Aula theatres in July / August and April / May respectively. The winners of the Serenade competition go on to represent the university at the National Serenade competition.<ref>[http://web.up.ac.za/default.asp?ipkCategoryID=2843&ArticleID=83 Serenade 2007 - Life is but a song! Retrieved 8 August 2010]</ref>

The university maintains the: UP Symphony Orchestra (UPSO), the only comprehensive student orchestra in Pretoria frequently performing symphonic repertoire,<ref name="upcoza-Orchestras">http://web.up.ac.za/default.asp?ipkCategoryID=9151&sub=1&parentid=7677&subid=7678&ipklookid=15 Orchestras. Retrieved 1 October 2009.</ref> UP Chorale, UP Brass Band, [[Tuks Camerata]],<ref>[http://web.up.ac.za/default.asp?ipkCategoryID=9150&sub=1&parentid=7677&subid=7678&ipklookid=15 Choirs. Retrieved 1 October 2009.]</ref> UP Children's choir, UP Concert choir and the UP Youth choir. The university supports, and has been host to the annual [[South African National Youth Orchestra Foundation|National Youth Orchestra]] course for a number of years.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.sanyo.org.za/about-us/history/| title=South African National Youth Orchestra Foundation - History| date=4 March 2009 | accessdate=20 March 2010}}</ref>

In addition to cultural activities students partcipate in several other non cultural activities.  The university organises the annual [[SAE International]] sanctioned student automotive engineering [[Baja SAE]] competition in South Africa sponsored by [[Sasol]].<ref>http://www.tuksbaja.co.za Tuks Baja. Retrieved 17 October 2009.</ref> Baja SAE is an intercollegiate and interuniversity design competition run by the Society of Automotive Engineers (SAE) where teams of engineering  students design, build and race small off-road cars.

;Student media
The '''Perdeby''', the official university newspaper, was founded in 1939<ref>[http://web.up.ac.za/default.asp?ipkCategoryID=9792 University of Pretoria Historical Overview Retrieved 1 October 2010]</ref> and has a readership of approximately 30 000.<ref>http://www.veldfiremedia.com/index.php/pretoria-university-student-newspaper-perdeby Perdeby Retrieved April 25, 2011</ref> [[Tuks FM]] (107.2[[FM radio|FM]]),the campus radio station, was established on 9 February 1981 and is run by university students out of the university's Student Centre.<ref>[http://www.tuksfm.co.za/Custom/history.html History Retrieved 1 October 2010]</ref>

;Civic service 
Civic service and outreach programmes are performed in the fields in which the University has proven competencies. These fields include professional associations, business and management and are performed in underdeveloped or developing communities.<ref>[http://web.up.ac.za/default.asp?ipkCategoryID=9758&subid=9758&ipklookid=2 More about the Department of Community Engagement. Retrieved 1 October 2009.]</ref>

==Sport==
[[File:DON-HPC.jpg|thumb|left| <center>The High Performance Centre on the LC de Villiers Sport Grounds </center>]]
{{main|Pretoria University F.C.}}
{{see also|FNB Varsity Cup}}

The University maintains a long tradition of student participation in sport and recreation. The University has 30 registered sport clubs and 10 academies, in which 9 000 students annually participate in on a competitive and recreational level,<ref>[http://web.up.ac.za/sitefiles/file/web-team/UP%20in%20a%20Nutshell%202009.pdf Up in a Nutshell 2009. Retrieved 17 September 2009.]</ref>  more than 1 000 volunteers are involved in sport in various designations and capacities. In 2007 University of Pretoria produced 93 Senior [[Protea]]s and [[Springboks]] and 4 [[South Africa national rugby union team]] (Springbok) Captains.<ref>[http://web.up.ac.za/UserFiles/100Eeufeesboek.pdf Centenary. Retrieved 1 October 2009.]</ref>The University sports facilities the LC de Villiers sports grounds, situated at an altitude of approximately 1,500m (4920ft) above sea level, were developed on an area of 760,000&nbsp;m<U+00B2>.<ref name="ReferenceC"/><ref name="autogenerated4"/> 

The university's High Performance Centre (HPC), which was established in 2002 has become the favoured location for the pre-departure camps of Team South Africa in addition to being chosen by several national and international federations as their preferred specialisation centre.<ref name="ReferenceC">http://web.up.ac.za/default.asp?ipkCategoryID=4916&subid=4916&ipklookid=14 Sport Facilities. Retrieved 1 October 2009.</ref><ref name="autogenerated4">[http://web.up.ac.za/default.asp?ipkCategoryID=4881&subid=4881&ipklookid=14 About Us. Retrieved 1 October 2009.]</ref><ref>[http://www.goal.com/en/news/1863/world-cup-2010/2010/06/07/1963066/world-cup-2010-party-atmosphere-as-argentina-train-in World Cup 2010: Party Atmosphere As Argentina Train In Pretoria Retrieved 11 June 2010]</ref> The HPC hosted the Argentinian national football team during the he [[2010 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1280607/Diego-Maradona-demands-1-600-luxury-toilets-World-Cup.html Diego Maradona demands luxury toilets be installed at World Cup training base Retrieved 28 December 2011</ref>

The HPC has a bifurcated role between hosting the TuksSport academies and hosting athletes and teams for pre-season or pre-event training. The HPC hosts the Institute for Sport Research, Sport Science and Medical Unit and the Sports Law Centre<ref>http://web.up.ac.za/default.asp?ipkCategoryID=4881&subid=4881&ipklookid=14 High Performance Centre Retrieved 28 December 2011</ref>

The High Performance Centre<U+2019>s TuksSport High School, established in 2002, is an independent specialised co-ed sports school catering for Grade 8 - 12 learners following the National Curriculum as offered by the Gauteng Department of Education. The school is supported by several national sporting federations and allows learners to train and travel internationally whilst staying in school.<ref>http://web.up.ac.za/default.asp?ipkCategoryID=8318&subid=8318&ipklookid=14 TuksSport High School Retrieved 28 December 2011</ref>
[[File:University of Pretoria Rugby.jpg|thumb|right|220px| <center>University of Pretoria Rugby team circa 1930</center>]]
Rugby is a particularly popular sport, and there are competitions between residences, faculties, and the University participates in the [[National Club Championships]], [[Carlton Cup]]<ref>http://web.up.ac.za/default.asp?ipkCategoryID=9476&ArticleID=8337 TuksRugby : UP-Tuks 1 defend cup title with emphatic win Retrieved September 30, 2011</ref><ref>http://web.up.ac.za/default.asp?ipkCategoryID=9476&ArticleID=8420 TuksRugby : UP-Tuks over first hurdle at Club Champs Retrieved September 30, 2011</ref> and the [[FNB Varsity Cup]] [[Rugby Union]] tournament, involving the top 8 rugby playing universities in the South Africa.

In 2002 the Uuiversity established the Tuks Football Academy and the [[University of Pretoria F.C.]] oginally playing in the SAFA Gauteng South Division. In the 2003-04 season the University acquired Pretoria City F.C.'s second division status, subsequently winning the National First Division (NFD) [[Vodacom League]] play-offs and being promoted to the NFD in 2004-05.  In the 2006-07 season the club qualified for the [[Mvela Golden League]] play-offs. In the 2008-09 season the club was a [[Nedbank Cup]] finalist losing to [[Premier Soccer League]] team [[Moroka Swallows]] 0-1.<ref>http://psl.co.za/content.asp?id=16586&comp=879 University of Pretoria FC Retrieved 20 November 2011</ref>

==Alumni and people==
{{expand section|date=June 2010}}
{{Main|List of University of Pretoria alumni}}
{{see also|List of Vice-Chancellors and Chancellors of the University of Pretoria}}
{| class="toccolours" style="float:right; margin-left:1em; font-size:90%; line-height:1.4em; width:300px;"
